               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184306120230"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1633" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1633" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1633" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1633" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS WHITE</persName>
                  </hi>. About ten o'clock, on the night of the 6th of June, I went to bed in a barge on the canal at West Drayton, Hillingdon—my things were safe in my cupboard a quarter of an hour before I went to bed—I awoke be<lb></lb>tween three and four and missed them—the key of the cupboard was in my trowsers pocket at the back of my head—I have seen the prisoner working on our canal—these are my trowsers—I had a ring like this in my pocket—I be<lb></lb>lieve this to be mine.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined</hi> by <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you any doubt about them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not any—I worked hard for the sovereigns—Soldier is a boatman who works about.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1634" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1634" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1634" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1634" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>ALFRED HUGHES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable D</hi> 174.) I found the prisoner outside the Red Lion, in the Edgeware-road, on the night of the 8th June—I said I should take him on suspicion of stealing 11<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and a quantity of clothes of Thomas White—he said, "Where?"—I said at West Drayton—he said, well, we could have a drop of beer and settle it—another boatman came out, and the prisoner said, "<hi rend="italic">Soldier</hi>, give him a shilling, and say you have not been able to see me"—I said he must go to the station—he said he would not—he sat down—another officer was opposite—I called him, and we took him—I found on him this ring, and part of the property—I then went to No. 7, Union-place, and asked for Mrs. Buck—I said I had come for a bundle that Williams had left her—she produced this bundle in the room on the first floor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did not the prisoner address <hi rend="italic">Soldier</hi> particularly about this matter? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not in my hearing—<hi rend="italic">Soldier</hi> is the nick-name of the boatman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1635" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1635" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1635" type="surname" value="BUCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1635" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY BUCK</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my mother, in Union-place. The prisoner brought this bundle on Wednesdy morning, the 7th of June.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Do you know this boatman they call <hi rend="italic">Soldier? A.</hi> Yes, I have known him for years—he worked where my father does.</p>
